</TABLE>
<PARA>Some examples of device names and their meanings are:</PARA>
<DEFLIST><DEFLISTENTRY><TERM><FILENAME>/dev/dsk/dks0d1s0</FILENAME></TERM>
<LISTITEM><PARA>The block device file for partition (slice) 0 of the SCSI disk on controller 0 at drive address 1.</PARA>
</LISTITEM>
</DEFLISTENTRY>
<DEFLISTENTRY><TERM><FILENAME>/dev/dsk/jag5d13s7</FILENAME></TERM>
<LISTITEM><PARA>The block device file for partition 7 (the entire disk except volume header) of the Jaguar disk on controller 5 at drive address 13.</PARA>
</LISTITEM>
</DEFLISTENTRY>
<DEFLISTENTRY><TERM><FILENAME>/dev/rdsk/dks0d2vh</FILENAME></TERM>
<LISTITEM><PARA>The character (raw) device for the volume header (partition 8) of the SCSI disk on controller 0 at drive address 2.</PARA>
</LISTITEM>
</DEFLISTENTRY>
</DEFLIST>
<PARA>Device file names for disks are symbolic links into the system hardware graph. For more information about this IRIX feature that describes the hardware entities on a system and their relationships, see <XREF LINKEND="LE58279-TITLE">. </PARA></SECTION>
</SECTION>
